 Many different mechanisms contribute to the etiopathogenesis of the so-called diabetic foot syndrome. Among chronic complications, the diabetic foot syndrome is one of the most frequent causes of hospitalization. The relative risk of diabetic patients requiring an amputation is up to 45 times greater than in normal subjects. Sensory neuropathy, ischemia, and infection are the principal pathogenetic factors in the diabetic foot syndrome. In most cases, a painless trauma is the initial condition that leads to an ulcer. In this article, an overview of the different causes, clinical manifestations, and treatment options for a multidisciplinary team are discussed.  
